  "target_response": {
    "text": "Yes — completely normal, and arguably the sign of a sprint session done properly. At the top of a maximal hill effort your heart is near its ceiling — your watch caught a peak of 187 bpm against your measured max of 194 bpm — and each beat is ejecting a lot of blood, which is exactly why you feel it thumping in your chest and throat. That sensation during deliberate max effort is your cardiovascular system working as designed. Context is what separates it from a symptom: it arrived when you demanded it, and it eased through your recovery jogs. Pounding that shows up at rest, wakes you at night, feels irregular, or comes with chest pain or dizziness is the version worth a doctor. What you're describing is just hill sprints doing hill-sprint things.",
